  <div id="grooming" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Grooming the Powder-Puff Coat in Our Humid Climate" imageAlt="Bichon Frise puppy having its curly white coat brushed during grooming" imageSrc={bichonGrooming} imagePosition="left">
      <p>We'll say it plainly: the Bichon Frise is the highest-grooming breed we carry, and pretending otherwise sells you the wrong dog. The curly double coat traps loose hair, which is why it barely sheds, and that same trap mats quickly if ignored. Brush 3 to 4 times a week, minimum, and book professional grooming every 4 to 6 weeks. Singapore's humidity speeds matting, so the routine matters more here than overseas care guides let on.</p>
      <p>The good news: most pet owners keep a shorter teddy trim rather than the show coat, which turns the routine into something genuinely manageable. Light tear staining shows on white faces; a daily wipe with clean water keeps it in check, and the tools you need are already in the starter kit.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>

  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" />
  <div id="health" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Bichon Frise Health: What We Check Before You Take One Home" imageAlt="Bichon Frise puppy at a veterinary health check before going home" imageSrc={bichonVet} variant="mid">
      <p>Every Bichon Frise goes home vet-checked, vaccinated, dewormed, and microchipped. The Bichon health points worth knowing are a small few: patellar luxation, a kneecap issue common to small breeds; dental crowding, so the oral care items in your kit matter; and skin sensitivities, which the grooming routine helps you catch early. We say this once, plainly, so you hear it from your seller and not from a forum later.</p>
      <p>Feeding is simple: your puppy comes with the small-breed food it is already eating, and any change should be gradual over a week. For portioning guidance see the <a href="/learn/puppy-health" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">puppy health checks explained</a> guide.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>
  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" flip />

  <CaptionedBlock heading="Your Bichon Frise's First Week at Home" imageAlt="Bichon Frise puppy settling into a set-up playpen during its first week home" imageSrc={bichonSettling} imagePosition="left">
    <p>Day 0: we deliver, free, at a time that suits you, usually morning or evening. The playpen, bed, water, and toys are set up before your Bichon explores the room, and we walk you through all 30+ starter-kit items in person. Learn more about <a href="/delivery" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">how our free home delivery and setup works</a>.</p>
    <p>Days 1 to 3: keep it calm and close. Bichons settle fastest with gentle company nearby, a fixed feeding routine, and the toilet pads where we placed them. Some night whimpering is normal adjustment.</p>
    <p>Days 4 to 7: the routine sticks. This is the window to book your free first lesson with an AVS-certified trainer; see <a href="/free-training" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">what the free AVS-certified training lesson covers</a>. For anything in between, you WhatsApp us.</p>
  </CaptionedBlock>

